Students and guests attend the forum on Friday. Photo: Courtesy of Zhang YanA group of well-known TV hosts, scholars and professors held a forum about the influence of today's booming short video industry in China at Beijing's Peking University on Friday, China's Journalists' Day.   The How to Be a Journalist Today forum was also attended by students from different universities in the capital. The forum's goal was to inspire these students to think deeply about their role in the future of the short video industry in China, which includes platforms such as TikTok and Pear Video. Bai Yansong, renowned TV host and also a researcher at the university's TV Research Center, Said that the transition between traditional and new media has brought about many changes, but the core responsibility of journalists to carry messages remains unchanged. Other topics included in-depth reporting and the challenges of journalism in the 5G era. Chinese scientists design gene-editing tool using light to kill cancer cellsAbsence at PLA maritime parade will prevent US from learning about Chinese Navy: expertsChinese American organization condemns increasing racial profiling in US Youth climate strikeAntique cars highlighted in US auto showsWildfire aftermath